<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-571-296  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 571 296.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 18 1990 v24 n25 p122(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Leading without bleeding: equipment arbitrage can let you upgradetechnology without red ink.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Oleson, Thomas D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Equipment arbitrage is an effective strategy for providing acompany with leading edge computer technology.andP;  Using thisapproach, a company purchases at deep discounts when a product isstill in an early stage of its lifespan, then sells or upgradesbefore the cycle of depreciation catches up.andP;  The result is toprovide the company with efficient technology at a minimal cost.andO;Volume purchase agreements and the utilization of third-partyremarketers, as well as a shortening of the depreciation cycle tothree or four years are the major components of this strategy.andO;The arbitrage strategy is only feasible in those instances wherethe mission of the company is one that supports a constant use ofleading edge equipment and technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TechnologyAutomationEquipment AcquisitionComputer IndustryCost ReductionStrategic Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>